##The fate of those who are not infected with NCP

Wechat, renwumag1980

Feature Introduction, the best Chinese character report

Non-pneumonia is a word that didn't exist before the outbreak. The new coronavirus reshapes the economy, public spaces, and People's daily lives, spreading like ripples, bringing people who once seemed to be on the periphery into the affected areas. Traffic Blockades, poor logistics, hospitals being requisitioned, doctors being transferred, problems appearing that affect people other than those with new pneumonia. HIV / AIDS, depression, pregnancy, cancer, kidney dialysis .... They're so different, no one would have thought they'd be lumped together.

By Xie Mengyao

Interview | Xie Mengyao, Wang Yujuan

Editor | Goldstone

Cinematography | Yoon hae-won

Out of the blue

It's either that or "I'm stuck on the table. ".

As he recalls the January 13 operation to decompress his extremely dangerous Crista, Ryu carefully eschews the word "dead. ". My wife, Yan Li, suffered from Pheochromocytoma, a disease whose cause was unknown and whose initial location was outside the peritoneum. At that time, the tumor had already compressed the column nerve, if not handled, her lower limbs may be paralyzed. Ritsuko knew that his wife was a very strong man, and he made the radical decision behind her back to postpone radiation, first through a surgical procedure, cutting through the spinal column, removing the tumor from the spinal canal and the nerve to avoid paralysis.

The good news is the surgery was a success.

For the Wuhan couple, who have just turned 30, the past six months have been a lifetime. At the end of July last year, Yan Li discovered an 8 cm tumor in her abdomen when she was three months pregnant. Both parents suggested terminating the pregnancy, and Yanli cherished the child and insisted that it be born. The operation was completed in mid August and the tumor was removed, but by November, Yan Li's cancer had metastasized to her bones and spread to her ribs, shoulders, liver and other parts of her body. The couple believed that was the price of pregnancy and that no treatment could be given, "catalysed it. ". By mid-december, there was no way, Yan Li early Cesarean section. Thank God the baby's okay. According to the original schedule, radiotherapy will be carried out after years. Yan Li is unable to move and has been living at the Wuhan Union Hospital.

The outbreak came out of nowhere. The opening of the radiotherapy center has been delayed. It was not until 5 February that the doors were finally opened, but because the first few patients received a diagnosis of pneumonia, the centre was again closed and fully disinfected.

In the meantime, l√º has received word that some hospitals in Wuhan have been ordered to treat new cases of pneumonia, and no more patients are admitted. He was glad that his wife was not in one of those general hospitals, "It's just a cancer hospital. On Feb. 9, when the Radiation Center reopened and the wife received radiation, "I was finally ready to start trying to control the tumor. "

The list of designated hospitals is expanding. The wife only had two rounds of radiation, and on February 13th, the Oncology Center was requisitioned.

It all seems to be happening so fast. There were three buildings in the cancer center, and one day people were posting the news on wechat groups. Ask the doctor and you won't get an accurate answer. The next day, all the patients were gathered in one building, "and suddenly it was very crowded and very noisy. ". The radiotherapy center is located on the subbasement level of the building where fever patients are treated. Law Law implicit hope, whether there is an opportunity to open a green channel, so that cancer patients continue to treat. On the Third Day, the Radiation Center closed.

"perhaps the hospital leaders also felt that the radiation treatment under the floor of the infected area would have to pass through the infected area. He couldn't take that risk, so he had no choice but to shut down the radiation center. "The lawyer thought.

Overnight, doctors who had been in and out of the ward suddenly disappeared. There were forty wards on the ground floor, and the lawyer saw only one doctor, busy with the discharge of patients. He just answered, "when this epidemic is over, you can come back. "

The hospital did not explicitly force the discharge, but in that case, everyone was busy packing up and assumed the situation could not be changed. "The patient intake will start that afternoon, and the ward will be renovated. If you don't leave, you have to leave. "

Panic is a given. Some people groan constantly, others cry to the doctor, "finally come to the doctor, AH, radiation treatment done half stop how to do? "? "

"In a place that saves lives, you feel like you're an outcast. "At that moment, not in anger, the lawyer had an incredible feeling that this matter had gone beyond what I could accept. He noticed that in the group of more than 100 patients, there were also patients from other places. Where will they go? Fortunately, he thought, he was from Wuhan and had a home to return to. Later, he was no longer able to pay attention to the whereabouts of those patients.

On the same day that Yan Li was discharged from the hospital, Tu Jing's cousin became a patient. Suspected leukaemia, this is a doctor according to clinical expression and blood routine examination to his judgement.

Even at this time, Tu Jing did not think that the epidemic would have a direct connection with the cousin. They live in a county town under Xiaogan, as if it were only 100 kilometers from Wuhan, where the outbreak began, but it is geographically and psychologically far away. A few days ago, the younger brother suddenly felt unable to move around and accompanied by a low-grade fever, the family once thought it was pneumonia.

When the plague was raging, the family's life was still peaceful and happy. During the Lunar New Year, the extended family did not take the strict self-isolation measures of city people, but also gathered together in the village to have a reunion dinner. The younger brother just had a wedding banquet more than a month ago. On the third night of the New Year's Day, the younger brother and his pregnant wife took a walk on the street in the county town. They shot a video and threw it into the group of relatives of over 20 people. "pneumonia" has never been a topic of discussion in this group. "We have no contact with the Wuhan people. "Tu Ching said.

On the night of February 3rd, he headed to Harvard Medical School, a top three hospital in downtown Xiaogan. After the bone marrow aspiration, the procedure jammed. In the past, the bone marrow puncture was sent to Wuhan for examination, but now, the logistics stopped, the examination of the docking hospital also stopped. Without a diagnosis, there is no treatment plan, the hospital can only give his brother some infusion and transfusion of basic treatment.

After that day, no one in the group spoke anymore. If you scroll forward, you'll find photos and videos taken not too long ago. "I didn't expect it so soon. I thought I could have a good life, " Tu said. "The lively scene makes a contrast. "

A different kind of person

At first, she could do what everyone else did, but retweet. Later, she decided she could do more than just hand it off. Chen Yijun, an overseas student in Australia, saw too many suffering people in the super-words of "help for pneumonia patients" on Weibo. She and her friends set out on a path to becoming Internet users, assembling help lists to get more attention.

Soon, Chen Yijun found that there were several volunteer groups on the Internet also seeking help for pneumonia. They had huge resources and mature operations, while he had "only one form. ". And in the process of collecting information, she also found that, in fact, a large number of non-pneumonia patients to help, mixed with the flood of information. There is almost no volunteering in this area. She and her friends decided to turn to this type of help. They gave the group, which has more than 20 members and exists only on the Internet, the tongue-in-cheek name "No red packets" .

The "No red envelopes" campaign was launched on February 12 and over 100 requests for help were collected in two days, making them aware of the urgency of the work. She had applied to set up a non-pneumonia helpline, and the page showed that forty thousand people were applying. For some reason, this super talk never held water. The volunteers had to rely on keyword searches, in a more primitive way, to find the voices that were asking for help. It was in this way that they found Tu Jing, which had only 12 fans. Some people send a request for help with a "help from a pneumonia patient" tag, giving them a chance to blend in with the established chatter. It was a last resort to get attention.

In an epidemic, the person with pneumonia is the first to be thought of, the person without pneumonia is another kind of person. The attention comes first, even the volunteers. Like "No red packets" , a volunteer group called "bed group" has experienced a shift from pneumonia to non-pneumonia issues. As its name implies, the organization does not interface with patients, but collects and publishes hospital bed information. They found that pneumonia patients were sent and hospitalized with community co-ordination, while non-pneumonia patients were more self-reliant.

A member of the "bed group" told people that in Wuhan at the end of January, it was still feasible for non-pneumonia patients to seek treatment across districts. In February, hospitals did not accept patients from other districts who sought treatment on their own, giving priority to people in the district -- as if on a curve previously experienced by new pneumonia patients -- is a testament to the increasing strain on medical resources.

To the volunteers'surprise, some of the requests came not from the outbreak but from the outside, as if in a chain reaction, with some patients having their operations cancelled because their doctors had been transferred to the front lines. A volunteer in Liaoning Province told l√º that his mother was one such case. People's cases also included a possible patient with a brain aneurysm in Guangshui, Hubei Province, who could not be operated on locally and was not accepted. According to reports, 10% of the country's critical care professionals went to Hubei, mainly in Wuhan.

After more than ten days, Chen Yijun and her friends felt extremely tired, which was a hard job with a sense of accomplishment. In particular, some large-scale surgery, "medical environment, medical resources, " only rely on the strength of volunteers to promote. Making phone calls is an important part of the limited list of things volunteers can do. Call the patient to update information and needs, and call the hospital to ask about receiving possibilities. The official list of available hospitals is just a name, with no phone numbers or other details. It takes a lot of effort to find a phone, "call whoever you can, " and some phones never get through. Later, "no Hongbao" made an online form to count the calls.

"No red envelopes" made posters about hospital admissions and bed information, but soon gave up. The pictures are beautiful and clear, but the drawbacks are obvious. "When this map is made, it will be there. Some people saw this picture of us and called to ask about it. As a result, the feedback from others was, it seems that this information of yours is not working now. "Chen Yijun said. Beds in hospitals change from hour to hour.

One volunteer told people that she had found a bed for an operation on a patient who had suffered a serious head injury in a car accident and found two hospitals acceptable at 6pm. After talking to patients, call again at 9:00 p.m. , one hospital has no beds, another hospital has a suspected pneumonia in the department, no new recruits.

At Best, you're a comfort, a guide. Tell him not to give up. "Chen Yijun said. Waking up every day, for a moment, the girl, who lives in a "well-fed, well-fed and well-weather" environment, has difficulty distinguishing between dreams and reality. While we waited, someone died, all the names she'd typed in. Sometimes, it's just her nightmares.

Sometimes, it's true.

Bridge-map source network for arranging medical information of patients with non-new coronary pneumonia released by bed group on Weibo

"Lucky. "

According to the experience of the "No red envelopes" voluntary organization, pregnant women's and children's requests for help are easily cause for concern, and the person concerned can often find a hospital to accept them.

For the rest of us, it's the drug-free patients that are relatively easy to deal with. They are mainly divided into several situations: People trapped in their hometown, the designated hospital to get medicine in another place; because the city is closed to the village, they can not go out to get medicine; or, the medicine is in short supply, in the local pharmacy can not buy.

We can find ways to help them buy drugs, or transport them. Chen Yijun said. The China Rare Disease Alliance launched a drug assistance program in early February to help more than 300 patients with rare diseases such as Acromegaly opposite of Microcephaly, Angel Syndrome and Myasthenia Gravis by contacting drug suppliers and coordinating drug distribution. Some gay rights groups have encouraged people living with HIV to borrow drugs from one another, and many of the appeals have been digested within communities.

Among the rest, another group that gained early attention was uremia patients who needed dialysis. On February 5, the Wuhan Municipal Commission of Health and Health announced the first targeted measures for patients with non-pneumonia, with chronic kidney failure patients (end-stage uremia) and pregnant and lying-in women highlighted.

According to Zhi'an, founder of the uremic friend platform "people like kidney" , there is an element of chance.

UREMIC patients need dialysis two to three times a week for about four hours each time. When the first two batches of hospitals in Wuhan were requisitioned, the affected patients could still find a place in other hospitals. The real dilemma arose when the third batch of hospitals were requisitioned at the end of January, "every available space in the area is filled by patients. ". The rest of the dialysis hospitals are working the night shift and still can't handle it. It's like a game of musical chairs, where the patients who are affected first, become the ones who sit first, and then the people who are affected, find themselves unable to find their seats.

The uremic community spoke before the problem became a problem. After Wuhan imposed restrictions, Zhi'an found a dozen media outlets, including ifeng.com and Nandu weekly, which first raised awareness of the group on social media platforms on January 27. Since then, several media outlets have published in-depth reports on the plight of dialysis patients. Under the struggle of Zhi'an, the Chinese Life Care Association submitted the internal reference.

At a news conference held by the National Health Commission on February 4, when a reporter asked about arrangements for pregnant women, the spokesman mentioned dialysis patients on his own initiative. "It means they had a plan in place before the press conference, otherwise he wouldn't have given those answers. "Chi on said. After that, the tendentious policy falls to the ground gradually, Wuhan's dialysis point increases obviously.

In the "no Hongbao" set up in the group of Hematology and dialysis help, Tu Jing saw that one by one uremic patients are being treated. "Are there very few patients with leukemia, and why aren't they getting attention and help? It's a big thing for us, it's like a speck of dust for the whole society, isn't it. "She thought.

"We called too early. Because the sooner you speak up, the louder you sound, the easier it is to be noticed. "Chi on said. "You will find that there is no voice in other patient groups, but some of them get media attention later on as they develop, but the effect is not good. Because energy, resources, and a lot of things are limited. Again and again, he used the word "lucky. ".

"kidney-like people" was established eight years ago, covering more than 50,000 people, and has patient groups in more than 80 cities across the country. The presence of a community can indeed have the effect of forewarning and amplifying the volume. In another example, as early as after the Lunar New Year, when many secondary problems related to the epidemic had not yet emerged, organizations such as the Wuhan Center for gays and Lesbians openly reflected the problem of drug withdrawal among people living with AIDS, which attracted media attention.

Another benefit of having community ties is in the collection and transmission of information. Which hospital opened up the dialysis room, and the patients came back with more accurate and faster information than the media. "For example, the other day, mitsuya sanitarium was requisitioned (dialysis is available) . After 10 p.m. , the information was sent out and the doctor informed the patient immediately. We will know. "Chi on said. Not to mention the sudden trauma of those seeking treatment, most chronic patients do not have such social conditions.

Chen Yijun, a member of "No red envelopes" , said that the dialysis problem was typical of being the first to be solved, and also because the operation was relatively simple, there were dozens of private dialysis institutions in Wuhan. In addition to the dialysis room, bedside dialysis is also possible. "For an operation, you need an operating room, you need multiple doctors, and you need good first-aid equipment. After the surgery, you can't go home right away, you have to observe, and that requires a whole series of treatments. "

In the middle

On paper, the dialysis problem seems to have been solved, with both the dialysis patients who were diagnosed with pneumonia and the dialysis patients who were not infected going their separate ways. But some find themselves in the middle, as if on pneumonia.

This was the case with Zhuang Biao's father. On the morning of February 7, the old man fell into a coma. One day earlier, he had just had dialysis in Wugang Hospital. Zhuang Biao rushed his father to Wugang Hospital for emergency treatment. He took a CT scan and found an infection in his lung. The unexplained coma may have added to the hospital's concerns, which have led to the ban on dialysis. Zhuang Biao told people that his father had had this lesion in his lungs since 2017.

They went to nine hospital, Florida, a targeted hospital for pneumonia, where dialysis could be done if the diagnosis was confirmed. But the father's nucleic acid test came back negative, and it's not accepted there either.

Logically, the approach of both hospitals is understandable. Wuhan Iron and Steel Hospital does not accept, is worried about suspected patients with the virus, infected with other healthy people. Nine hospitals do not accept, is worried that suspected patients are not sick, came but by other patients infected. Logic doesn't work in the real world, where the father isn't going anywhere.

Time went by little by little. The father had a fever the next day, but it soon subsided and never returned. On the third day, my father, who had been in a coma, came to. He's acting like he's lost his mind. Zhuang Biao later found out that his father had eaten all his mother's sleeping pills that night, and that the long suffering of chronic diseases and sudden outbreaks had made him decide to die.

When Zhuang Biao asked for help on Weibo, which has been viewed more than a million times, he was hopeful. After the volunteers intervened, they made a number of calls with him, including to a hospital in a remote county, which they were unable to receive. Zhuang Biao gradually recognized this reality: "They certainly do not want to bear the risk, so only in the original dialysis hospital to try to eliminate (suspected) as soon as possible. ". "

At some point, Zhuang Biao really thought, if his father can be diagnosed on the good, although more a heavy suffering, at least there is a place for dialysis. He doesn't think it's ridiculous to think that, because "it's hopeless, it's hopeless. ". Of course, he went back and forth to the community. "until further notice. "He was always told. The Qingshan District, Wuhan Health Commission, the National Health Commission and the Wuhan Center for Disease Control and Prevention, where the Wuhan Steel Hospital is located, like all callers, have had more than one call. It's either too "up, " or it's not the right "up. ". Where's the real one? He figured out that Wuhan Dialysis Quality Control is responsible for dialysis patients all over the city.

The institution is attached to the first hospital. He called and said, "that's not up there, either. " It was just a dialysis call. He didn't know anything.

It's hard to shake off that feeling of inferiority. Once he and his mother ran to the Wuhan Steel Hospital Dialysis Director Communication, the other side directly said: "What are you here, do not harm people. ". It's nobody's fault. In Times of crisis, people's nerves are frayed. Mother argued with the director, and he watched her cry. Later, he cried, too.

By February 12, my father had been in nine hospitals, Wuhan Iron and Steel Hospital and street health stations have done three nucleic acid testing, all negative. Is that a blessing? Now do nucleic acid testing is much easier, if the nucleic acid reagents back to the very poor stage, the diagnosis is no way, Zhuang Biao thought, "that time will be more trouble. ".

But the flip side of the coin is that hospitals no longer believe in nucleic acid results after the false negative problem emerged. Wuhan Iron and Steel Hospital initially told Zhuang Biao, two tests were negative, Zhuang Biao father can go back to dialysis, later changed to 3, finally said, or according to CT judgment.

Especially when it comes to transfers, many hospitals are wary of patients'NUCLEIC ACID test results. A patient with a head injury from a car accident suffered a similar episode. He was originally admitted to Golden Beach Hospital for treatment of pneumonia, but was not responsible for surgery. The nucleic acid test was negative on February 16. He was asked to leave the hospital, but on February 19 he was found in two hospitals with beds because he had a fever, they're all asking him to retest it. The results from three days ago are not reliable.

Zhuang Biao finally found the "top" . The volunteer gave him a number that belonged to the director of the hemodialysis quality control center. The phone's working. He was told that they did not interface with patients, but only coordinated vacancies between the hospitals.

He stopped tweeting. The traffic was growing, and he felt the light of hope dimming.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Medical staff in Wuhan Hospital

Break through

But from the tumor center after discharge, Law Thought of the place is the parents-in-law home, there are elderly help, convenient to take care of his wife. When he got there, he realized he couldn't get up the stairs. The wife was unable to move and lay on a stretcher, while the in-laws lived in a building without a stretcher elevator (1.1 m 2.1 m) , only a square elevator, stretcher can not enter. It's a neighborhood less than 10 years old. In the end, they had to go home.

The stretcher lift is a metaphor for neglected needs. He had noticed that there was no rectangular elevator in the building where his in laws lived, but he never realized that it had become difficult. "A lot of things can only be understood if they happen to you. "In a mature city, there are people in the health care system who shouldn't be in this position in the first place, " he said. "

After a round of phone calls, "the response was that all hospital radiation treatments had stopped. ". "

Tu Jing, of Xiaogan County, is still trying to get her brother's bone marrow aspiration tested. She found out that there are some third companies in Wuhan that can carry out such tests. When she contacted one, she was told, "most people are doing nucleic acid tests for pneumonia. The phenomenon of resource skewing also exists in this market. When she heard later that the hospital did not approve of such third-party testing, she gave up entirely.

There's only one way to go. Tu Jing and LV LV both thought of this way: to seek medical treatment outside the province.

We have to act now. Traffic Control is getting tighter and tighter. From about mid February, Tu Jing's county seat was closed to traffic from 7:30 a.m. to 6:30 p.m. She works at the bank, gets off at 5:30, and has to wait an hour to get home. Because of the traffic, she never had a chance to visit her brother in the city hospital. In Wuhan, the law from home to the hospital, law has been stopped by traffic police. He doesn't have an epizootic pass. "technically, he's not allowed on the road. ". After explaining the circumstances to the traffic police, he was released, but was told it would never happen again.

At this point, the two families'experiences diverged.

Yan Li's high school classmates spontaneously organized a group of more than 20 people from all walks of life to spread the news. LV LV's cousin is a media person. With the help of her inner circle, LV's appeal for help has been reposted on Weibo, which has been viewed millions of times. His appeal for help has also attracted the attention of the Qingshan district government. He was contacted by a person in charge, and he was very nice, "in Qingshan District, Wuhan, if the police impound your car, you call me and I'll fix it. " . "

Through multiple connections with relatives in Beijing, they reached the head of a Beijing hospital, where a more targeted form of isotope whole body radiation, introduced in the United States, will have beds by the end of February. A friend of the public security system sent a message, as long as the Beijing hospital can open admission certificate, Hubei Exit, and even along the way he can help solve.

These are only oral promises, and the law is particularly excited by the response of the traffic control team of the Wuhan Epidemic Prevention Headquarters to the wife's case through the official account of the Toutiao: "My team recommends that the hospital issue the relevant medical certificate, after approval by the municipal and district Epidemic Prevention Headquarters, my group will contact the relevant citizens to coordinate the issue of release. To him, the reply was like a special pass.

Very few people get such an arrangement.

Tu Jing was frustrated. She had been to two provincial hospitals and had had a good talk with them, but when she heard that the patient was from Hubei, the other side said it was unacceptable. Tu Jing didn't look any further. She knew that even if she passed the acceptance test, her brother would not survive the 14-day quarantine.

The help that is published on the net, basic did not forward and message. Authorities were aware of her condition, and the hospital was questioned. There was probably some misunderstanding in the message, she got a call from her cousin's father, who was in the hospital, asking if she had complained. Though she thought all she had done was ask for help, "she didn't say anything bad, " she deleted the post.

After a while she regretted it and sent the request for help again, but there were few retweets and messages.

The local police station and Xiaogan City Health Commission is to take the initiative to call Tu Jing. From beginning to end, she told the story twice more. They were thorough. They called the hospital. However, Tu Jingxin knows that the crux is in Wuhan, only the brother bone marrow puncture test can be achieved, things can progress, otherwise "continue to investigate, there is no result. ".

Two very different storylines merge into one. There was a twist in the wife-lawyer's provincial road to health care: Street leaders at the Beijing hospital disagreed. "Beijing is relatively relaxed for people from other provinces. People from Wuhan are still strictly not accepted. "probably thought we were going to bring pneumonia, " said lawyer. "He had a lot of responsibility. "

At about the same time, l√º saw that the Wuhan Epidemic Prevention Headquarters abolished a notice concerning the management of vehicles leaving the city (Order 17) , which meant the tightening of the management of the channels away from Han.

The empty streets of Wuhan

Connecting flight

The situation of non-pneumonia patients has gradually improved as the epidemic has been brought under control and the "take it all" policy for pneumonia and suspected patients has been implemented.

On February 18, the Wuhan Municipal Health and Health Commission issued for the second time a list of hospitals for treating special patients with non-new-crown pneumonia, covering more types of diseases than the first time, the list of emergency treatment hospitals for patients with acute cardiac cerebrovascular disease, trauma, renal disease patients with hemodialysis needs, pregnant and lying-in women, children, patients with facial diseases, burn patients, etc. . On February 21, the municipal epidemic prevention headquarters set up a "non-new pneumonia medical treatment team" .

After the new measures are introduced, it still takes time to break in. According to the "No red envelopes" volunteers, the government announced that a number of trauma and other critical care hospitals, in fact, can only accept general trauma emergency treatment, not major surgery. With a large number of hospitals and health-care personnel serving pneumonia, bed resources for non-pneumonia patients remain scarce.

As for non-pneumonia patients outside Wuhan, they have not received the same attention because of their dispersion. Tu Jing's brother is still in Xiaogan hospital blood transfusion, can not be confirmed. The good news is that -- if that's any good news -- she tweeted on February 23rd, this time with the hashtag pneumonia help, and thousands of retweets. There have been fewer calls for help lately, but there are others. "One user retweeted.

After a break of Dialysis for eight days, the Wuchang Hospital finally agreed to let Zhuang Biao's father go back to dialysis. A room had been set aside for the father and several other suspected patients, and the nurses worked in protective clothing. My father was weak and seemed to Groan and Groan during dialysis, and at one point asked for it to end 20 minutes early. He cries on his own sometimes. Zhuang Biao thought, since can isolate dialysis, why not do it earlier, the father would not suffer so much. But then he thought, "well, there are people involved, and they're afraid to take it. ". "

On February 21, Yan Li was admitted to Puren Hospital, where she was given radiation treatment under government coordination. L√º felt that there was always a threshold in his heart he could not cross. "when an event erupts, the resources and power of the society will be concentrated at that point. This is a good thing, but this degree is always not well grasped. "everyone is equal, " said the lawyer. "It is hard to feel neglected. It is hard to feel neglected. "

The law still hopes that the blockade will be lifted and that his wife will go to Beijing for more advanced treatment. Previously, he had focused on Wuhan, but now he is closely linked to the changes in Beijing. He began to pay special attention to a place where he had never lived. First thing in the morning, I look at the pneumonia numbers, see if the numbers in Beijing have decreased.

"I hope this epidemic will soon be over, " l√º said.
